{{Infobox person | name = | native_name = Ɛli Azayku | birth_date = 1942 | death_date = 2004 | nationality = Moroccan | occupation = poet, historian, philosopher }}
'''Ali Sidqi Azaykou''' ({{Lang-ber|Ɛli Azayku}}; 1942–2004), also called '''Dda Ali''',<ref name="dai">« Hommage. Azayku l'Amazigh » par Maria Daïf, ''TelQuel'' n°147 [http://www.mondeberbere.com/azayku_telquel.html].</ref> was a Moroccan [[Berber people|Berber]] poet, historian, philosopher and critic. He was an Amazigh activist.<ref>Conscience et revendication de l'identité berbère.</ref> He has greatly influenced the cultural Berber movements.<ref>[http://www.tamaynut.org/article.php3?id_article=104 « Génération Amazigh »] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071007190923/http://www.tamaynut.org/article.php3?id_article=104 |date=2007-10-07 }} - ''HH / Tel Quel'' n° 184, août 2005.</ref>
== Biography == Ali Sidqi Azaykou was born (1942) in the village of Igran n tuinght in the [[High Atlas]] in the surroundings of [[Taroudannt]] in the [[Sous]] region in [[Morocco]].<ref name="lef">[http://www.mondeberbere.com/azayku_bio_en.html Claude Lefébure, ''Méditerranéennes'' n°11, hiver 1999/2000, Paris]</ref> He began his primary education in his native village and ended them in [[Marrakesh]] where he also followed his secondary education and entered the national teacher training college.<ref name=dai/>
==Books== {{Moroccan literature}} * {{lang|fr|Timitar}}. Collection of Berber poetry. 1988. * {{lang|fr|Relation de voyage du Marabout de Tasaft dans le Haut-Atlas}}. Éd. de la Faculté des Lettres, [[Kénitra]], 1992. * {{lang|fr|Izmulen}}. Collection of Berber poetry. Rabat, 1995. * {{lang|fr|Histoire du Maroc et ses possibles interprétations}}. Recueil d'articles. Éd. Centre Tarik Ibn Zyad, Rabat, 2002. Introduction by [[Ahmed Toufiq]]. * {{lang|fr|L'islam et les Amazighs}}, 2002. * {{lang|fr|Quelques exemples de toponymes marocains}}, 2004. * {{lang|fr|Petit dictionnaire arabe/amazigh}}, Éd. Annajah Al Jadida, 1993, Casablanca.
