'''Chinese Cultural Fever''' - ( {{Lang-zh|s=文化热|t=文化熱|p=wén huà rè}})  was a cultural tendency in [[China]] in the late 1980s, started with [[Chinese economic reform|economic reforms]]. It can be considered the first independent cultural initiative in China since 1949. After a period of isolation, China opened to [[Western philosophy|Western Thought]]. This tendency ended in 1989 due to the a sudden change of political climate, visible in the [[1989 Tiananmen Square protests|1989 Tiananmen Square protests.]]

==Literature==
* Zhang X. On Some Motifs in the Chinese "Cultural Fever" of the Late 1980s: Social Change, Ideology, and Theory. Social Text. No. 39 (Summer, 1994), pp.&nbsp;129–156.
* Zhang X. Chinese Modernism in the Era of Reforms: Cultural Fever, Avant-Garde Fiction, and the New Chinese Cinema. 1997.
* Wang J. High Culture Fever: Politics, Aesthetics, and Ideology in Deng's China. 1996.
* Chang L. Culture fever // Encyclopedia of contemporary Chinese culture. Compiled by EdwART. 2011. http://contemporary_chinese_culture.academic.ru/165/culture_fever

