{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox museum |name = Elsecar Heritage Centre |image = Elsecar Heritage Centre.jpg |imagesize = 240 |caption = Elsecar Heritage Centre |map_type = |map_caption = |latitude = |longitude = |established = |dissolved = |type = [[Heritage centre]] |location = [[Elsecar]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]], [[England]] |visitors = |director = |curator = |publictransit = |website = [http://www.elsecar-heritage-centre.co.uk Elsecar Heritage Centre] }} '''Elsecar Heritage Centre''' is a [[living history]] centre in [[Elsecar]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]], England.
==Heritage Centre== The buildings were originally used for various industries including [[ironworks]] and [[forge]]s, a [[distillery]], and engineering workshops. These fell into decline when the [[coal mines]] in the village closed.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.elsecar-heritage.com/|title=Elsecar - Official website|last=Jepson|first=Ledgard|website=www.elsecar-heritage.com|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.barnsley-museums.com/elsecar|title=Barnsley Museums - Official website - Elsecar|last=Jepson|first=Ledgard|website=www.barnsley-museums.com|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>
It has its own [[Elsecar goods station]] (called Rockingham Station) on the [[Elsecar Steam Railway]], with a running shed behind the main centre. During some special events, trips are run to [[Hemingfield|Hemingfield Basin]]. There are plans to extend the line to [[Cortonwood]] and build two stations (one at Cortonwood and the other at Hemingfield). The railway's depot is home to a selection of [[steam locomotive]]s as well as a [[diesel locomotive]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elsecarrailway.co.uk/|title=Home|website=www.elsecarrailway.co.uk|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>
It comprises [[retailing|shops]], galleries, art studios and an exhibition hall. It runs [[craft]] workshops, special events, and a monthly [[antiques]] fair.
Elsecar Heritage Centre hosts the [[16 mm scale|16mm]] [[Garden railway|Garden Railway]] Show every year which is organised by the Yorkshire Group of 16mm Narrow Gauge Modellers Ltd.
In March 2017 it was announced that the ''Great Place Scheme'' a partnership between [[Arts Council England]], the [[Heritage Lottery Fund]] and [[Historic England]] was to jointly fund [[Wentworth Woodhouse]] and Elsecar Heritage Centre with a £1,264,000 grant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.greatplacescheme.org.uk/more-information-about-great-place-scheme|title=More Information about the Great Place Scheme {{!}} Great Place Scheme|website=www.greatplacescheme.org.uk|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherham.gov.uk/news/article/1140/south_yorkshire_villages_of_elsecar_and_wentworth_to_receive_funding_of_12_million|title=South Yorkshire villages of Elsecar and Wentworth to receive funding of £1.2 million|last=Ellis|first=Joanne|website=www.rotherham.gov.uk|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/southyorkshire/culture/venues/a_f/elsecar_heritage_centre.shtml|title=BBC - South Yorkshire Culture - Elsecar Heritage Centre|work=BBC News|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>
===Elsecar Engine=== [[File:Elsecar Newcomen engine.jpg|alt=Elsecar Newcomen engine|thumb|Elsecar Newcomen engine]] The centre is also the site of the only [[Newcomen steam engine|Newcomen beam engine]] in the world still in its original location. The Newcomen Engine was built at the instruction of [[William Fitzwilliam, 4th Earl Fitzwilliam|William Wentworth, the 4th Earl Fitzwilliam]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.barnsley.gov.uk/media/4049/elsecar-appraisal-draft2.pdf|title=Elsecar Appraisal|last=|first=|date=|website=Barnsley Council|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref> It was used to pump water out of [[Elsecar New Colliery]] and ran from 1795 until 1923 when it was replaced by electric pumps. The date over the door of the Engine House is 1787, but there is some dispute that the engine was not actually installed until 1795.<ref name=":1" /> In 1836 the Graham brothers, a local partnership cast a new beam and two parallel motions for the Newcomen engine.<ref name=":0" /> It also ran briefly in 1928 when the electric pumps were overwhelmed by flooding. At its peak it could draw 600 gallons a minute. In 1972 the engine was classified as a [[scheduled ancient monument]]. The engine was restored to working order (worked by [[hydraulics]]) over the period 2012&ndash;14.<ref>{{cite journal|first=Alan|last=McEwen|title=Elsecar's Newcomen engine restored|journal=Old Glory|issue=299|date=January 2015|pages=6-7}}</ref><ref>{{PastScape|mnumber=314723|mname=ELSECAR COLLIERY PUMPING ENGINE|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-18526408|title=Elsecar's 'outstanding' relic for restoration|date=20 June 2012|work=BBC News|access-date=20 March 2017}}</ref>
