{{Infobox French commune |name = Lunel |commune status = [[Communes of France|Commune]] |arrondissement = Montpellier |canton = Lunel |image coat of arms = Blason ville fr Lunel (Hérault).svg |image = Mairie lunel.JPG |caption = Town hall |INSEE =34145 |postal code = 34400 |mayor = Claude Arnaud |term = 2014&ndash;2020 |intercommunality = Pays de Lunel |coordinates = {{coord|43.6778|4.1361|format=dms|display=inline,title}} |elevation min m = 2 |elevation max m = 53 |area km2 = 23.90 |population = 24873 |population date = 2014 |demonym = }}
'''Lunel''' ([[Provençal dialect|Provençal]]: ''Lunèl'') is a [[Communes of France|commune]] in the [[Hérault]] [[Departments of France|department]] in southern [[France]]. According to legend, Lunel was founded by [[Jews]] from [[Jericho]] in the first century.<ref>{{cite book |last=Farber |first=J.B. |title=The Pope's Jews in Provence: Itineraries |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4axqMcS-1n8C |year=2013 |publisher=Editions Actes Sud |location=Arles |isbn=2330018975 }}</ref> It had a Jewish population by the first millennium, and an ancient synagogue is located there.
[[File:Map commune FR insee code 34145.png|thumb|left|350 px|Map]] {{clear-left}}
Lunel is located {{convert|21|km|mi|abbr=on}} east of [[Montpellier]] and {{convert|28|km|mi|abbr=on}} southwest of [[Nîmes]] ([[Gard]]).
==History== The ancient Roman site of [[Ambrussum]] is located nearby. The [[troubadour]] [[Folquet de Lunel]] was from Lunel.
Lunel was a centre of Jewish learning. It is thought that the family of [[Rashi]] (1040–1105), the great [[Rabbi]] and [[meforshim|commentator]], originated in Lunel. Other scholars include [[Jonathan ben David ha-Cohen|Jonathan of Lunel]], [[Meshullam ben Jacob]] of Lunel, his son [[Aaron ben Meshullam ben Jacob of Lunel]], [[Abraham ben David]] who taught in Lunel before moving to Posquières, and [[Asher ben Meshullam]] of Lunel.
Lunel was the birthplace of [[Louis Feuillade]] (1873&ndash;1925), [[film director]] from the [[silent film|silent era]]. The artist [[Jean Hugo]] (1894-1984) lived in the Lunel area for most of his life and painted scenes from the surrounding countryside. The Parc Jean Hugo in the centre of the town was named after him.
Since the 20th century, the town has been a destination for Muslim immigrants from Algerian and other parts of North Africa. In 2015 the ''New York Times'' reported that 10% of all the French people killed fighting in Syria for [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIS]] came from Lunel.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/17/world/europe/french-town-struggles-over-departures-for-jihad.html?_r=0 "A French Town Linked to Jihad Asks Itself Why"], ''New York Times,'' January 2015</ref>
