'''Nikolay Fyodorovich Bugay''' {{lang-ru|Никола́й Фёдорович Буга́й}} (born 19 December 1941) is a Russian historian. He is Doctor of Historical Sciences, Chief Researcher at the Institute of History of the [[Russian Academy of Sciences]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://iriran.ru/?q=bugay|title=Бугай Николай Федорович {{!}} Институт российской истории РАН|trans-title=Nikolay Fyodorovich Bugay {{!}} Institute of Russian History|date=2015|website=Институт российской истории РАН|publisher=Institute of Russian History of the Russian Academy of Sciences|language=Russian|accessdate=2016-03-07}}</ref> and adviser of the Department of Interethnic Relations of the Ministry of Regional Development of Russia.

== Early life ==
Born in [[Starotitarovskaya]], [[Krasnodar krai|Krasnodar Krai]], Bugay graduated from the Kabardino-Balkarian State University in 1968.

== Career ==
He has worked as a scholar in multiple universities. He published numerous academic works on Stalinist repression and [[Joseph Stalin|Stalin's]] deportations of the people within the USSR (Koreans, Germans, Meskhetian Turks, Crimean Tatars etc.)

In 1996, he was awarded the title, "Honored Scientist of the [[Adygea|Republic of Adygea]]", and in 2009, the Board of Starotitarovskaya rural settlement awarded him a commemorative diploma: "The title of Honorary Citizen of the village Starotitarovskaya, Temryuk district for his contribution to the history and culture of his native village."

